\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Introduction
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\
More and more cultural institutions use linked data principles to share and connect their collection descriptions. In the archival field, initiatives emerge to exploit data contained in archival descriptions and adapt encoding standards to the semantic web. In this context, online authority files can be used to enrich metadata. However, relying on decentralized knowledge bases such as Wikidata has its own difficulties due to their broken-world character: absent or conflicting data require a permanent investment in maintenance and repair [D. LOVINS and D. HILLMANN, Broken-world vocabularies]. Our presentation aims to offer a critical view of these linked data by adopting a close-reading approach. Through a practical case-study, we intend to identify and illustrate the possibilities and limits of RDF triples compare to institutions' less structured metadata.\'a0\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \
\pard\tx566\tx726\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Our paper is an invitation to travel in an unexpected way: diving through the Linked Open Data cloud, with the help of Alex, a robot. This robot uses SPARQL endpoint to jump from one \'91set\'92 of RDF triples to another. Before starting this exploration\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
, we would like to first introduce you to Henry Carton de Wiart, a famous Belgian personality. Part of a large noble family, he has been minister several times, Prime Minister, president of many councils and organisations, and a lawyer and a writer as well. As you may know, the Belgian city Li\'e8ge owes its nickname to one of his books, La Cit\'e9 ardente. Moreover, he has been honored by several awards and was in contact with many well-known personalities, from the poet Verlaine to the President Wilson. His life contains therefore sufficiently life facets in order to act as a case study to compare how linked open data can reconstruct a biography compared to more traditional information sources.\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\
While many studies about Linked Open Data adopt approaches based on methods such as data mining or network analysis, they tend to analyse the data quality of cultural heritage linked data only through the prism of quantitative and comparative analysis \cf3 [inclure un exemple typique pour appuyer le propos ?]\cf0 , without taking an in-depth qualitative perspective. In this paper, we opt for a close-reading approach focusing on a single individuality and its data quality, in order to analysis how the triple structure succeeds to capture biographical data, compare with more traditional authority files. \cf3 The paper is structured as follows: \'85\'85..\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sa280\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \

\b Continuum\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sa240\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 This paper wishes to reflect on the continuum of different documentation practices and methods, from the traditional paper-based narrative to very structured data which are currently published as triples in a knowledge graph. At one end are situated unstructured data, like the national biography of Henry Carton de Wiart, 8 sheets of well-written text, which have been digitised end published online in a PDF version [cf. r\'e9f\'e9rence : http://www.academieroyale.be/Academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2102.pdf, p. 86-94]. At the other end, stand the most structured data, which correspond to Linked Data, such as the Wikidata item attributed to Henry [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q14990"}}{\fldrslt https://wikidata.org/wiki/Q14990}}], the Viaf entity [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://viaf.org/viaf/24623115/"}}{\fldrslt https://viaf.org/viaf/24623115/}}] or the french DBpedia page [http://fr.dbpedia.org/page/Henry_Carton_de_Wiart]. In between, are established more isolated structured data like RDF triples from archives or libraries repositories [e.g. Data.bnf.fr : {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://data.bnf.fr/12062835/henry_carton_de_wiart/"}}{\fldrslt http://data.bnf.fr/12062835/henry_carton_de_wiart/}}], archival descriptions in XML [e.g. the EAC-cpf file from the State Archives of Belgium: the https://search.arch.be/eac/xml/eac-BE-A0500_007556_FRE.xml] or Wikipedia pages [e.g. the english version: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Carton_de_Wiart"}}{\fldrslt https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Carton_de_Wiart}}]. \
While the most structured resources display facts (such as a birth date or death date) very clearly, in a machine-readable format, we can wonder if they provide as many details as a more classical format type, such as the national biography: do they mention its Hennuy\'e8res origins, his correspondence with an apostolic vicar living in Brazzaville, or that day in August 1914 when the Belgian king asked him to lead an extraordinary mission to the United States? This question can be mapped to the central premise of Lev Manovich\'92s book \'ab\'a0The Language of New Media\'a0\'bb, in which he describes the tension between traditional narratives and databases \cf3 (reference).\cf0  Through this case study, we aim to extend this thinking and confront various forms of structured sources and to observe to what extent they are consistent and complementary. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sa240\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 Diving into the LOD cloud\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\sa240\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 Alex-the-robot, the main character of our case-study, can be seen as a fictional cousin of these famous "robot journalists". If Alex existed, it would share with them this ability to produce texts which are not written by a human, but by an algorithm. Where a robot journalist produces, for example, weather reports, election results or financial reports, Alex would write biographic texts based on information extracted from the Linked Open Data cloud. It will proceed like a historian who collects pieces of information from various sources, in order to gradually be able to write the portrait of an individual. The only difference is that instead of skimming several resources, Alex would perform queries on the web and then interpret the results, as long as they are in a structured format, such as XML or JSON. Indeed, \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 like all robots, he does not understand natural language. However, it is able to write basic sentences based on structured data like RDF triples. It means therefore that Alex is able to write, for example, that someone was born that year, in that location, and practiced this or that job.\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 His personal skills having been reviewed, Alex is now ready to begin his dive into the Linked Open Data cloud. His mission is to collect as much triples as possible about our man, Henry Carton de Wiart. Its starting point will be DBpedia. Indeed, this knowledge base is often considered as the focal point of the Linked Open Data cloud, towards which converge links from many databases. Thus, we will ask Alex to go to the Carton de Wiart's DBpedia page, to collect RDF data from this page and then to follow all links to external databases.\
\
Figure 1 shows all the links between knowledge bases. As aforementioned, the entry point is DBpedia. All the paths explored by Alex are visible. From DBpedia, Alex goes to various versions DBpedia in other languages, then to Yago, to Freebase (which no longer exists) and finally to Wikidata. In our figure, the size of each node is proportional to the number of outgoing links to other databases. The size of Wikidata's bubble means it contains a lot of external links: to VIAF, BNF or the Library of Congress authority ID. Whenever our robot comes in a knowledge base, it collects all the information it finds : Henry Carton de Wiart is a politician; he was born in Brussels; he wrote the novel 'La Cit\'e9 ardente'.\
\
\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\partightenfactor0

\b \cf0 RDF triples harvesting\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 \
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx1700\tx2267\tx2834\tx3401\tx3968\tx4535\tx5102\tx5669\tx6236\tx6803\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 During this process, Alex harvested more than 22,000 RDF triples about Carton de Wiart. While this amount can seem huge, it has to be noted that the vast majority of these triples are meaningless. RDF can be a verbose format, requiring something a lot of different triples to express something quite basic. Thus, once the useless triples have being eliminated, there are about 1,500 triples left, which use some 240 distinct properties. \cf3 (Explain more in detail, based on examples, what these useless triples are)\cf0 \
\
However, these properties are often redundant. In order to get a global view of their  nature, we have developed a tyopology of eleven broad categories: affiliations; appellations; category, dates; descriptions; identifiers; locations; miscellaneous; professions; relations; works. Figure 2 shows the proportion of triples in each of these categories. Triples have been placed in their respective category according to the property used in the triple. For instance, the property \'ab\'a0
\i http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label
\i0 \'a0\'bb correspond to the "appellation" category, which encompasses all the different labels under which Henry Carton de Wiart is known. There are many, especially in VIAF, which records the different labels used by libraries: Carton de Wiart\uc0\u8207 , Henry\u8207 ; Carton de Wiart, Henry,\u8207   Comte, 1869-1951\u8207 ; Carton de Wiart, Henry\u8207 \u8206   (1869-1951). The "category" category is the largest because it includes Wikipedia links, i.e. links to other pages or categories contained in Wikipedia. It also includes Yago categories, which are numerous, for example, "Henry Carton de Wiart is a legal Actor", or "Henry Carton de Wiart is an Aristocrat".  \
