\b \cf0 3// The vocabulary\
	\
\pard\tx566\tx1133\tx10701\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf0 To express facts about someone in RDF triples, several RDF vocabularies can be used to specify the relationship between a subject and an object.\
-Again, we have noticed some limits related to granularity. \
Thus, in the family context, depending on what vocabulary we used, we were able to specify that someone was an uncle, OR merely describe the fact that he was a relative. In this case, we would lose details and have uncle and cousin described by the same vague property. In the field of social relationship, one vocabulary called 'relationship' allows us to qualify 'acquaintance of', 'friend of', 'a close friend of', 'has met', etc.  Although this representation is useful, sometimes it appears quite difficult to evaluate the specific nature of a relationship between two dead people... \
\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 - \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
During the triplification process, most of the data has been translated in RDF triples without issues. In a few cases, we lacked vocabulary terms to express more atypical statements, such as details about Henry\'92s personality, or mentions about his activism in the context of social struggles. \
\pard\tx566\tx1133\pardeftab720\sl360\slmult1\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Obviously, it raises the question of the long tail\'85 to what extent should we create new properties for each specific case?\
